{"slug": "scroll", "root": "scroll", "category": "book", "gloss": "a rolled manuscript", "definition": "A *scroll* is a rolled manuscript: a continuous length of papyrus or parchment wound around a rod and read by unrolling. It is the format the bound *codex* displaced in late antiquity, and it survives in magic as the shape of the written charm — a strip of inscribed words worn on the body, buried, or held aloft in ritual.", "history": "Middle English *scrowle*, an alteration of *scrowe*, 'a scrap or strip', reshaped under the influence of *rolle*, 'a roll'. The turn is that the scroll marks the losing side of a media war: the emperor Augustus is said to have burned two thousand magical scrolls in a single year, and the last rolls of Alexandria perished with the Serapeum. Yet the rolled strip kept its power in ritual — curse tablets were rolled up as scrolls, and amulet-scripts were worn against harm. The name endures in Magic's *Scroll* artifacts, and in the verb we now do to a glowing screen.", "def_sources": [{"label": "Richard Kieckhefer, Magic in the Middle Ages", "where": "Medieval magic (PDF)"}, {"label": "John G. Gager, Curse Tablets and Binding Spells", "where": "Renaissance magic (PDF)"}, {"label": "Etymonline, s.v. scroll", "where": "Etymology reference"}], "is_keyword": false, "etymology": {"origin": "Middle English scrowle, alteration of scrowe ‘scrap’, influenced by rolle ‘roll’", "first": "late 14c.", "note": "The scroll’s name records the losing side of a media war — the format the codex replaced, now revived only in the verb we do to phones.", "hook": "We ‘scroll’ our phones with a dead book-format’s name.", "lang": "French"}, "essay": null, "sources": ["Etymonline (Douglas Harper)", "Wiktionary", "classical lexica (Lewis & Short, LSJ, Bosworth–Toller)", "Ted's historical-magic DBs (WitchcraftStudiesDB, AgrippaDOP, MedievalMagicDB)"], "stats": {"flavor_total": 21, "oracle_total": 8, "in_flavor_cards": 20, "in_oracle_cards": 4, "name_match_count": 1